00:46:31,653 --> 00:46:33,474
designed our last DLC that just came out.

965
00:46:33,474 --> 00:46:36,736
You'll see people on Discord basically say,

966
00:46:36,736 --> 00:46:38,437
like, hey, post your, you know,

967
00:46:38,437 --> 00:46:39,558
for new players who are having a hard time,

968
00:46:39,558 --> 00:46:40,878
post your replay, I'll take a look at it,

969
00:46:40,878 --> 00:46:43,019
I'll give you advice.

970
00:46:43,019 --> 00:46:44,961
It's just, you know, community is important.

971
00:46:44,961 --> 00:46:46,701
I mean, people understand that.

972
00:46:46,701 --> 00:46:47,982
All right, so.

973
00:46:48,311 --> 00:46:50,714
probably some things we do differently about early access

974
00:46:50,714 --> 00:46:55,118
if we did it again. One is we had basically a full QA pass.

975
00:46:55,118 --> 00:46:59,343
We would do kind of a big monthly updates. Which meant we

976
00:46:59,343 --> 00:47:01,645
kind of did a full QA pass because we wanted them to be

977
00:47:01,645 --> 00:47:02,866
polished. And

978
00:47:03,627 --> 00:47:07,851
that's fine but it's kind of grueling on the team to put them through that process. You're

979
00:47:07,851 --> 00:47:13,756
releasing every month, we're a small team, we want to be moving quickly. So we did a couple

980
00:47:13,756 --> 00:47:17,760
things to help ourselves out. We had a next version branch which is basically one we could

981
00:47:17,760 --> 00:47:21,443
update whenever we wanted to without going through QA because you had to opt into it. So

982
00:47:21,443 --> 00:47:26,147
that helped. But I think that next time around probably what I would do is I would just have a

983
00:47:26,147 --> 00:47:28,849
build machine that automatically updates the public version every Monday.

984
00:47:29,661 --> 00:47:33,304
and if there's a problem, just do a roll back or a hot fix.

985
00:47:33,304 --> 00:47:36,688
Like, it's okay, I've found, you know,

986
00:47:36,688 --> 00:47:39,190
if you're in touch with the community, like, it's okay.

987
00:47:39,190 --> 00:47:42,013
Like, I think that they're generally forgiving of problems

988
00:47:42,013 --> 00:47:42,833
if you're responsive.

989
00:47:43,354 --> 00:47:47,677
I would probably also wait a little bit longer to go up in

990
00:47:47,677 --> 00:47:53,742
early access. Be aware that your only free press hit comes when

991
00:47:53,742 --> 00:47:56,084
you launch on early access. That's kind of like when the

992
00:47:56,084 --> 00:48:00,087
press conceive of you as a new game. A lot of the big

993
00:48:00,087 --> 00:48:03,169
YouTubers and streamers were only interested in the game the

994
00:48:03,169 --> 00:48:05,531
first time around. When we had the final launch they kind of

995
00:48:05,531 --> 00:48:09,174
had moved on basically. In some cases you have the worst cases.

996
00:48:09,174 --> 00:48:11,616
We had one very prominent YouTuber viewer.

997
00:48:11,956 --> 00:48:13,739
people ask when it came out in early access,

998
00:48:13,739 --> 00:48:15,522
hey, are you going to review this?

999
00:48:15,522 --> 00:48:18,207
And he said, oh, I don't do reviews of early access games.

1000
00:48:18,207 --> 00:48:21,392
But then when we came out for real,

1001
00:48:21,392 --> 00:48:23,176
he basically had forgotten about it.

1002
00:48:23,176 --> 00:48:24,498
So, you know, that can happen.

1003
00:48:26,778 --> 00:48:28,860
This is how I like to do early access.

1004
00:48:28,860 --> 00:48:32,723
Which is, the more steps you have from testing a game

1005
00:48:32,723 --> 00:48:34,665
internally to releasing it, the better.

1006
00:48:34,665 --> 00:48:38,789
You want a whole bunch of smaller incremental steps

1007
00:48:38,789 --> 00:48:40,390
to get to the final release.

1008
00:48:40,390 --> 00:48:43,734
What we did was this.

1009
00:48:44,394 --> 00:48:46,997
We had a private beta, and then we jumped all the way

1010
00:48:46,997 --> 00:48:47,978
to early access.

1011
00:48:47,978 --> 00:48:50,981
And I would really like to have two steps in between there,

1012
00:48:50,981 --> 00:48:51,862
at least.

1013
00:48:51,862 --> 00:48:53,744
A public beta, where we're like, OK, now we're

1014
00:48:53,744 --> 00:48:55,646
going to show our game publicly and let you buy it

1015
00:48:55,646 --> 00:48:58,309
through our site, the way a game like Factorio work,

1016
00:48:58,309 --> 00:48:58,689
for example.

1017
00:48:59,450 --> 00:49:02,151
And then the next step would be like an unlisted Steam page,

1018
00:49:02,151 --> 00:49:04,492
which is the idea that your game's up on Steam,

1019
00:49:04,492 --> 00:49:06,133
people can buy it, but only if they have

1020
00:49:06,133 --> 00:49:07,274
like an external link to it.

1021
00:49:07,274 --> 00:49:09,675
Kind of like one of those like private YouTube videos

1022
00:49:09,675 --> 00:49:11,656
you can only watch if you happen to have the link.

1023
00:49:11,656 --> 00:49:14,497
And your game wouldn't show up on Steam in like searches

1024
00:49:14,497 --> 00:49:17,319
or in the top sellers or it wouldn't be promoted,

1025
00:49:17,319 --> 00:49:18,159
that type of thing.

1026
00:49:18,279 --> 00:49:20,442
So that's a great way to kind of like have that stream

1027
00:49:20,442 --> 00:49:21,042
infrastructure.

1028
00:49:21,042 --> 00:49:23,104
There's a lot of players who don't want to buy a game

1029
00:49:23,104 --> 00:49:25,727
until it's on Steam, period, end of story.

1030
00:49:25,727 --> 00:49:28,430
So if you have this, you're able to pull in those players,

1031
00:49:28,430 --> 00:49:30,853
even if you're not kind of like getting the full on hit

1032
00:49:30,853 --> 00:49:32,034
of being up on early,

1033
00:49:32,034 --> 00:49:34,096
the full on pressure of being up on early access.

1034
00:49:35,931 --> 00:49:37,712
So this is kind of an interesting question.

1035
00:49:37,712 --> 00:49:39,754
We were $40 in early access, which was like,

1036
00:49:39,754 --> 00:49:43,516
made us one of the absolutely most expensive games on there.

1037
00:49:43,516 --> 00:49:45,197
And I think you can, if you want to,

1038
00:49:45,197 --> 00:49:46,518
charge less when you're in early access

1039
00:49:46,518 --> 00:49:48,439
and then raise the price, which is unusual.

1040
00:49:48,439 --> 00:49:49,980
You don't normally get a chance to do that,

1041
00:49:49,980 --> 00:49:53,022
but I think you can pull it off there.

1042
00:49:53,022 --> 00:49:55,904
But I'm not sure if we should have lowered the price

1043
00:49:55,904 --> 00:49:58,746
because although it did, having a high price

1044
00:49:58,746 --> 00:50:01,328
definitely hurt our review score on Steam,

1045
00:50:01,328 --> 00:50:02,188
but it definitely kept.

1046
00:50:03,357 --> 00:50:05,097
We didn't have too many players to deal with.

1047
00:50:05,097 --> 00:50:07,238
The players that we got during the early access

1048
00:50:07,238 --> 00:50:09,359
were really what I call high quality players.

1049
00:50:09,359 --> 00:50:10,919
They were ones who wanted to be part

1050
00:50:10,919 --> 00:50:12,620
of the development process,

1051
00:50:12,620 --> 00:50:15,061
and they were good to work with.

1052
00:50:15,061 --> 00:50:17,162
So I'm kind of unsure about this.

1053
00:50:18,142 --> 00:50:20,624
But this is kind of like my big general feeling about early

1054
00:50:20,624 --> 00:50:22,486
access and about games in general.

1055
00:50:22,486 --> 00:50:25,528
Eventually your players always understand your game better

1056
00:50:25,528 --> 00:50:26,469
than you do.

1057
00:50:26,469 --> 00:50:29,672
And being able to do early access means you're like fully

1058
00:50:29,672 --> 00:50:31,033
committing to that truth.

1059
00:50:31,033 --> 00:50:33,895
Like that's just the way it is whether you like it or not.

1060
00:50:33,895 --> 00:50:38,399
I also have some suggestions for what Valve should do.

1061
00:50:38,399 --> 00:50:41,201
As I mentioned, the unlisted store pages, as I understand,

1062
00:50:41,201 --> 00:50:43,283
I think this might actually be happening now.

1063
00:50:45,612 --> 00:50:48,234
I also think there should be an early access category for reviews.

1064
00:50:48,234 --> 00:50:53,097
Qualities of games can go up and down over time and it makes a lot of sense that a game

1065
00:50:53,097 --> 00:50:56,299
when it was early access is going to be better after release than before release.

1066
00:50:56,299 --> 00:51:00,402
So I don't see why you wouldn't want to just have a separate category for those type of

1067
00:51:00,402 --> 00:51:01,823
reviews.

1068
00:51:01,823 --> 00:51:05,625
And I also think there shouldn't be sales or refunds during early access.

1069
00:51:05,625 --> 00:51:10,008
This is a quote from a Subnautica developer and he points out that, you know...

1070
00:51:10,853 --> 00:51:13,655
When you lower the price, you get a group of people

1071
00:51:13,655 --> 00:51:16,417
who are less dedicated to your product,

1072
00:51:16,417 --> 00:51:18,098
and there's a pretty good chance

1073
00:51:18,098 --> 00:51:19,619
you're gonna leave a negative view,

1074
00:51:19,619 --> 00:51:21,380
because they didn't really research it.

1075
00:51:21,380 --> 00:51:23,401
They didn't really know what they were getting into.

1076
00:51:23,401 --> 00:51:26,543
And I'd say that the goal here

1077
00:51:26,543 --> 00:51:29,485
is actually to get fewer players.

1078
00:51:29,725 --> 00:51:32,108
You know, you want there to be kind of a bigger hurdle

1079
00:51:32,108 --> 00:51:35,072
for people to buy your game, Windows on Early Access,

1080
00:51:35,072 --> 00:51:37,255
so they know they're doing something different.

1081
00:51:37,255 --> 00:51:38,818
They're not just buying a game on Steam,

1082
00:51:38,818 --> 00:51:41,541
they're buying a game that's in development.

1083
00:51:41,541 --> 00:51:44,726
Like, so I would be totally happy with, you know.

1084
00:51:44,806 --> 00:51:48,428
kind of like a smaller group of players in early access that are more committed to the

1085
00:51:48,428 --> 00:51:53,650
development process. Also, be good to your early access customers. When we released, we

1086
00:51:53,650 --> 00:51:59,853
automatically upgraded them all to the deluxe edition. They started off immediately with

1087
00:51:59,853 --> 00:52:07,937
soundtrack and the DLC that we launched. These are your best fans. Treat them well. So speaking

1088
00:52:07,937 --> 00:52:09,998
of reviews, I want to mention a few things about them.

1089
