00:56:33,021 --> 00:56:36,303
different random game mechanics, why do you make games at all?

1184
00:56:36,303 --> 00:56:40,425
You know, and so I often get asked whether off world is a

1185
00:56:40,425 --> 00:56:43,667
free trade game or an anti-capitalist game or some

1186
00:56:43,667 --> 00:56:44,908
other statement on the world economy.

1187
00:56:45,649 --> 00:56:47,990
And I don't think games should be trying to make broad

1188
00:56:47,990 --> 00:56:51,032
statements like, you know, capitalism is good or capitalism

1189
00:56:51,032 --> 00:56:54,855
is bad. It's just too simplistic. And also the game

1190
00:56:54,855 --> 00:56:57,937
designer has too much power to set up the rules to support his

1191
00:56:57,937 --> 00:56:58,978
or her own biases.

1192
00:57:02,091 --> 00:57:03,952
This is what I think off world is about.

1193
00:57:03,952 --> 00:57:04,912
The prices tell a story.

1194
00:57:04,912 --> 00:57:07,633
You know, in off world, if iron costs more than steel,

1195
00:57:07,633 --> 00:57:09,674
then something has gone wrong.

1196
00:57:09,674 --> 00:57:11,955
And you win by taking advantage of these discrepancies.

1197
00:57:11,955 --> 00:57:15,136
You know, that puts you in the shoes of a business person,

1198
00:57:15,136 --> 00:57:17,557
which is really sort of the best that a game can do.

1199
00:57:17,557 --> 00:57:19,358
You know, there's a reason why everything costs

1200
00:57:19,358 --> 00:57:19,818
what it does.

1201
00:57:19,818 --> 00:57:22,559
You know, sometimes that goes beyond supply and demand,

1202
00:57:22,559 --> 00:57:25,600
to government policy, and cultural factors.

